{{Infobox language |name=Nupbikha |region= [[Bhutan]] |speakers=2,200 |date=2006 |ref=e18 |familycolor=Sino-Tibetan |fam2=([[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman]]) |fam3=[[Tibeto-Kanauri languages|Tibeto-Kanauri]] |fam4=[[Bodish languages|Bodish]] |fam5=[[East Bodish languages|East Bodish]] |script=[[Tibetan script]] |iso3=npb |glotto=nupb1238 |glottorefname=Nupbikha }} The '''Nupbi language''' ({{lang-dz|nupba'i kha}} "Western language") is an [[East Bodish languages|East Bodish language]] spoken by about 2200 people in central [[Bhutan]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=npb |title=Nupbikha |publisher=[[SIL International]] |work=[[Ethnologue]]: Languages of the World |editor=Lewis, M. Paul |year=2009 |edition=16 (online) |location=[[Dallas, Texas]] |accessdate=2011-09-26}}</ref>
Historically, Nupbikha and its speakers have had close contact with speakers of [[Bumthang language|Bumthang]], [[Kurtöp language|Kurtöp]] and [[Kheng language|Kheng]], nearby languages of central and eastern Bhutan, to the extent that they may be considered part of a wider collection of "Bumthang languages." The [[Nyen language]], also related to the Bumthang languages, is more divergent, while the [['Ole language]] ("Black Mountain Monpa") is only distantly related.<ref>{{cite book|title=Bhutan: Mountain Fortress of the Gods |first=Christian |last=Schicklgruber |editor=Françoise Pommaret-Imaeda |publisher=Shambhala |year=1998 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8Q1uAAAAMAAJ |pages=50, 53}}</ref><ref name=EEL>{{cite book|first=George |last=van Driem |authorlink=George van Driem |editor-last=Moseley |editor-first=Christopher |contribution=Endangered Languages of Bhutan and Sikkim: East Bodish Languages |title=Encyclopedia of the World's Endangered Languages |year=2007 |page=295 |publisher=[[Routledge]] |isbn=0-7007-1197-X |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6LoNl7ZRO70C}}</ref><ref name=vanDriem2007>{{cite book|title=Language diversity endangered |volume=181 |series=Trends in linguistics: Studies and monographs, Mouton Reader |authorlink=George van Driem |last=van Driem |first=George |page=312 |editor=Matthias Brenzinger |publisher=Walter de Gruyter |year=2007 |isbn=3-11-017050-7 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6p6b5GQ4Q4YC}}</ref>
